1.What is the syntax of a method in Java, and what are its main components?
-->A method in Java is a block of code that performs a specific task and can be called when needed.

    ✅ Syntax of a Method:
    returnType methodName(parameters) {
        // method body
    }
    🔍 Main Components:
    Return Type
    Specifies what the method returns
    Example: int, void, String
    Method Name
    Name of the method (identifier)
    Parameters
    Inputs passed to the method (optional)
    Method Body
    Code that defines what the method does
    ✅ Example:
    int add(int a, int b) {
        return a + b;
    }
    
    👉 In short:
    Method = return type + name + parameters + body



2.What is the difference between instance methods and static methods in Java?
-->Instance Method:
    Belongs to an object (instance) of a class
    Requires object creation to call
    Can access both instance and static variables
    
    Static Method:
    
    Belongs to the class, not objects
    Can be called without creating an object
    Can access only static variables directly


3. Difference Between Method Declaration and Method Definition?
-->Method Declaration:

    Specifies method name, return type, and parameters
    Does not contain the body
    Example:
    int add(int a, int b);
    
    Method Definition:
    
    Contains the actual implementation (body)
    Example:
    int add(int a, int b) {
        return a + b;
    }


4. Can a Java Method Have Multiple Return Statements?
-->Yes, a Java method can have multiple return statements, but only one executes based on the condition.

    Example:
    
    int checkNumber(int num) {
        if (num > 0) {
            return 1;
        } else if (num < 0) {
            return -1;
        } else {
            return 0;
        }
    }


5. Access Modifiers in Java Methods & Their Visibility
-->Access modifiers control where a method can be accessed from.

    Types:
    
    public → accessible everywhere
    private → accessible only within the same class
    protected → accessible within the same package and subclasses
    default (no modifier) → accessible within the same package only



